{{distinguish|jersey (fabric)}}
A '''jersey''' is an item of [[knit]]ted [[clothing]], traditionally in [[wool]] or [[cotton]], with [[sleeve]]s, worn as a [[Sweater|pullover]], as it does not open at the front, unlike a [[Cardigan (sweater)|cardigan]]. It is acommonly worn by sports teams as part of the team uniform, in team colors, often with a required number and optionally the player's name on the back. It is usually close-fitting and machine knitted in contrast to a [[guernsey (clothing)|guernsey]] that is more often hand knit with a thicker [[yarn]]. The word is usually used interchangeably with [[sweater]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0040517507078023|title=Studies on the Influence of Knit Structure and Stitch Length on Ring and Compact Yarn Single Jersey Fabric Properties|first1=C.D.|last1=Kane|first2=U.J.|last2=Patil|first3=P.|last3=Sudhakar|date=1 August 2007|publisher=|journal=Textile Research Journal|volume=77|issue=8|pages=572–582|via=SAGE Journals|doi=10.1177/0040517507078023}}</ref>

==In sports==
{{wide image|NBA Jerseys.jpg|750px|A sports fan's collection of NBA basketball jerseys}}


{{see also|Third jersey|Baseball uniform|Uniform (American football)|List of Major League Baseball retired numbers}}
Alternatively, a jersey as used in [[sport]] is a [[shirt]] worn by a member of a team, typically depicting the [[sportsperson|athlete]]'s name and team number as well as the [[logotype]] of the team or corporate sponsor. [[Cycling jersey]]s of specific color or pattern represent certain statuses in [[cycling]], such as the yellow jersey of the leader of the [[general classification in the Tour de France]], or the [[rainbow jersey]] for the world champion.  Cycling jerseys are usually made of synthetic [[microfiber]] material to aid in wicking sweat away from the skin to allow it to [[evaporate]].  The main garment of an [[ice hockey]] uniform, which was traditionally called a sweater, is increasingly known as a [[hockey jersey]]. This garment, along with [[basketball]] jerseys which are usually [[sleeveless]] and [[baseball]] jerseys which are usually button up, have become fashion accessories. A related term is "[[Bib (garment)|bib]]", which may refer to a shirt (jersey, esp. in Britain{{citation needed|reason=Lived here all my life, never once heard anyone use bib to mean shirt/jersey|date=February 2018}}). In [[Australian rules football]], the player's shirt is known as a "[[guernsey (Australian rules football)|guernsey]]".<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1177/004051755502500314|title=An Engineering Approach to Jersey Fabric Construction|first=W.E.|last=Shinn|date=1 March 1955|publisher=|journal=Textile Research Journal|volume=25|issue=3|pages=270–277|via=SAGE Journals|doi=10.1177/004051755502500314}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hemdvoorhem.nl/|title=Hemdvoorhem.nl - Gratis verzending en 100 dagen gratis retour|website=www.hemdvoorhem.nl}}</ref>

In some sports, such as [[ice hockey]], [[baseball]], [[basketball]], and various [[football]] codes, a player's jersey may be "[[retired number#See also|retired]]".  When a jersey is retired that player's jersey is placed usually where the team plays in honor of that player's accomplishment.  Generally, when a jersey is retired, the [[Number (sports)|number]] on the player's jersey is made unavailable for future players.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=jaCjAgAAQBAJ|title=Textiles in Sport|first=Roshan|last=Shishoo|date=29 August 2005|publisher=Elsevier|via=Google Books}}</ref>

